A landmark UK Supreme Court ruling has reignited the gender identity debate, declaring that “woman” in the Equality Act refers strictly to biological sex. Trans women—even those with Gender Recognition Certificates—are no longer legally considered women under this definition. With implications for everything from women’s spaces to representation quotas, this ruling marks a seismic shift in the cultural and legal landscape. How did we get here—and what comes next?
